<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910812-0054</DOCNO><DOCID>910812-0054.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Norfolk Southern Corp.:   Rail Unit Is to Buy Rest   Of Shares of Wabash Line</HL><DATE>08/12/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4</SO><CO>   NSC WA+</CO><MS>INDUSTRIAL (IDU)</MS><IN>RAILROADS (RAI)STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)</IN><NS>STOCK andamp; OTHER MARKET NEWS (STK)ACQUISITIONS andamp; MERGERS, TAKEOVERS, BOARD BATTLES (TNM)</NS><RE>NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)VIRGINIA (VA)</RE><LP>   Norfolk andamp; Western Railway Co., based in Norfolk, Va., saidit reached a definitive agreement to buy the remaining commonand preferred shares of Wabash Railroad Co. that it doesn'talready own.   The companies said their boards approved a definitivemerger agreement. Norfolk andamp; Western, a unit of NorfolkSouthern Corp., already owns 99% of Wabash's common sharesand 66% of the preferred. The previously reported merger willbe voted on at a special meeting of Wabash shareholdersscheduled for Nov. 12.</LP><TEXT>   Under the proposed agreement, each Wabash preferred sharenot owned by Norfolk andamp; Western will be converted into a rightto receive $75 in cash plus accrued dividends. Additionally,each Wabash common share not owned by Norfolk andamp; Western willbe converted into a right to receive cash equal to 10.155times the closing price of Norfolk Southern.   Wabash owns rail lines in the Midwest that are leased toand operated by Norfolk andamp; Western.</TEXT></DOC>